# Fat-Client-First Architecture Rule

The application architecture must remain:

1. Browser-based fat client as the primary/full client.
2. Remotely launchable but locally executed client runtime.
3. A reduced app-profile variant (subset of full fat-client capabilities).

## Required architecture constraints

- Keep domain/UI logic local-first and browser-executed.
- Allow remote delivery/launch of client assets without moving execution to server-side rendering.
- Support local resource access (storage/cache/local processing) behind explicit client APIs.
- Keep resource loading/saving strictly in the client runtime (no backend dependency for local resource handling).
- Keep top-level `resource/` as the canonical PGN resource library.
- Keep canonical resource kinds explicit as `file`, `directory`, and `db`.
- Keep metadata schema/constants centralized in `resource/domain` and consumed by frontend boundaries.
- Keep SQL schema/migration ownership in `resource/database/` (never in frontend feature modules).
- Support integration of remote resources (services/APIs/content/providers) via explicit adapter boundaries.
- Maintain a reduced app profile with clear feature boundaries relative to full client.
- Keep full-client and app-profile compatibility explicit (feature flags/capability matrix or equivalent).

## Delivery checks before finalizing changes

- Full fat-client browser path still runs with `npm run dev` and `npm run build` in `frontend`.
- Reduced app-profile path still runs with `npm run desktop:dev` and packages with `npm run desktop:pack` in `frontend`.
